Diving deep: gradient fluctuations¶

Date: Oct 18th, 2020

Table of contents:

  • Setting up
  • Increasing std
  • Decreasing std, ways to mitigate vanishing
  • Increasing mean

So here, we will see how and when gradient vanishing happen, and also discuss ways to mitigate them. This post should be short and simple.

Setting up¶

In [1]:
import torch
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

Here, we have a function that generates normal distributions and multiply all of them together. For each time that we multiply, we then record both the means and stds, so the function returns 2 1d-arrays:

In [6]:
def generate(mean, std, n=60):
    answer = torch.ones(10000); means = []; stds = []
    for i in range(n):
        answer *= torch.normal(mean, std, (10000,))
        means.append(answer.mean()); stds.append(answer.std())
    return means, stds

And this is to analyze a particular means and stds config. This just generate means and stds 10 times, and graph them so we know how they should normally behave. Then 1 particular sample is returned so we can see the general trend:

In [7]:
def stats(tensor): return tensor.mean(), tensor.std()
def tensorListToList(array): return [np.round(tensor.numpy(), 7) for tensor in array]
def analyze(mean, std, meansLimit=None, stdsLimit=None):
    mss, sss = [], []
    for i in range(10):
        ms, ss = generate(mean, std)
        mss.append(ms); sss.append(ss)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 3), dpi=100)
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1); [plt.plot(ms) for ms in mss]; plt.title("Means"); plt.ylim(meansLimit) if meansLimit != None else 0
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2); [plt.plot(ss) for ss in sss]; plt.title("Stds"); plt.ylim(stdsLimit) if stdsLimit != None else 0
    ms, ss = generate(mean, std)
    return tensorListToList(ms[::10]), tensorListToList(ss[::10])

Let's see this in action in the default case of $(0, 1)$:

In [12]:
analyze(0, 1)
Out[12]:
([0.004726, 0.0126579, 0.0006867, 0.0005367, 3.8e-06, 3.5e-06],
 [0.9986122, 0.8883221, 0.0660638, 0.05001, 0.0004166, 0.0003388])

So this is the "ideal" behavior from the literature. Every tensors are normalized to $(0, 1)$, and in theory the standard deviation has to be stable over time. But turns out, it still decays, albeit slowly.

Increasing std¶

A natural thought might be increasing the standard deviation by a little bit, to may be 2?

In [16]:
analyze(0, 2)
Out[16]:
([0.0095322, -17.631884, -300.59048, 310314.2, 9175759.0, 166745020.0],
 [1.9897563, 1617.3905, 127801.805, 20253316.0, 1017396700.0, 23813517000.0])

Yeah that didn't last well. Everything blows up to $+\infty$. So let's see a few values from 0 to 1:

In [17]:
analyze(0, 1.5)
Out[17]:
([0.0017371, -0.427477, 2.1624246, 5.883277, -112.252625, 1299.6624],
 [1.490578, 37.923653, 579.9135, 9879.253, 11245.935, 124914.44])

This is still quite unstable as a neural net with any $10^6$ weights or activations are screwed.

In [18]:
analyze(0, 1.2), analyze(0, 1.1)
Out[18]:
(([-0.0030959, -0.0162459, -0.1905757, 0.1055798, -0.0022609, 0.0008708],
  [1.2028304, 5.366212, 17.05924, 8.938676, 0.2515804, 0.0668345]),
 ([0.008258, -0.0589207, -0.0133605, 0.0022202, -0.0004418, -1e-07],
  [1.1051639, 2.4711137, 0.7671497, 0.1446666, 0.0292719, 0.0005711]))

This is more moderate. In a few $(0, 1.2)$ runs, stds can get as high as 500. Still bad for neural nets, but not unworkable bad like $(0, 1.5)$ case. $(0, 1.2)$ does better to keep the signal running than $(0, 1.1)$, but only for an additional 10 layers, and $(0, 1.1)$ is only 10 layers deeper than the ideal case of $(0, 1)$. So it seems like messing up the distributions is not a good way to extend the signal. Let's now lower the std instead.

Decreasing std, ways to mitigate vanishing¶

In [19]:
analyze(0, 0.9), analyze(0, 0.8)
Out[19]:
(([0.0011083, 0.0025329, -0.0001738, 5.1e-06, 0.0, 0.0],
  [0.907491, 0.3374758, 0.0128589, 0.0015061, 4.5e-06, 1e-07]),
 ([-0.008414, -0.0011584, 1.96e-05, 3e-07, 0.0, 0.0],
  [0.8101226, 0.1005627, 0.0012118, 1.4e-05, 2e-07, 0.0]))

Oh no, not good. $(0, 0.8)$ basically goes to nothing after only 10 layers. This is worrying, and exactly why it was hard to train deep CNNs back in the AlexNet days. Why am I analyzing $(0, 0.8)$? Because in the industry, that's the best neural nets can behave.

So after passing through 1 linear layer, the activations follow the above analysis of $(0, 1)$, if you initialize them correctly. But you have to then pass that through an activation function, or all those linear transformation afterwards become meaningless. So let's test it out:

In [20]:
def relu(tensor): return (tensor > 0) * tensor
x = torch.normal(0, 1, (10000,)); stats(x), stats(relu(x))
Out[20]:
((tensor(0.0035), tensor(1.0045)), (tensor(0.4015), tensor(0.5941)))

Now our std is not 1, but is far less than that, at 0.6. Kaiming He sort of disgrees with our fate, and decided to put a $\sqrt2$ in front:

In [21]:
stats(relu(x) * np.sqrt(2))
Out[21]:
(tensor(0.5678), tensor(0.8402))

So there's that 0.8 that everyone has been using. It's not so bad though, it's not as if $(0, 1)$ can extend the signal to infinity either. So clearly a better method needs to be in place. This is exactly what resnet did back in 2015. That Kaiming guy realized that by adding skip connections, an infinite layer network can trick mathematics to see it as having only 1 layer, and because $(0, 0.8)$ extends to well beyond the first 10 layers, this is good enough, and made resnet won ImageNet that year.

Increasing mean¶

Let's tweak the mean a little bit, just for curiosity sake:

In [29]:
analyze(0.5, 1), analyze(0.6, 1), analyze(0.7, 1)
Out[29]:
(([0.477026, -0.0864195, 0.0121777, -0.0012479, 8.02e-05, -9.33e-05],
  [1.0034102, 13.394275, 1.1058192, 0.2778655, 0.0849103, 0.0056078]),
 ([0.6012863, -0.0344355, -0.0550536, -0.036129, 0.0009148, 1.11e-05],
  [0.9991372, 3.7942245, 8.531518, 3.12163, 0.2148822, 0.008277]),
 ([0.6804134, 0.0069895, -0.0397755, 0.1368064, -0.1559509, -0.1466025],
  [0.9966327, 5.7475286, 9.293692, 13.099258, 15.007835, 14.94821]))

Increasing mean to around 0.5 to 0.6 is sort of okay, but increasing it further will start to make the network unstable.

In [31]:
analyze(1.5, 1), analyze(1, 0.3)
Out[31]:
(([1.4992676, 87.548, 5004.954, -1906214.9, 64492304.0, -2086105700.0],
  [0.9993644,
   577.37415,
   253857.61,
   153094770.0,
   6751010300.0,
   355184870000.0]),
 ([0.9976493, 1.0148268, 1.0315311, 1.0374521, 0.9812232, 0.989132],
  [0.3010534, 1.3230047, 2.2125, 3.2678869, 4.0571237, 6.2263236]))

The above 2 graphs is meant to demosntrate that the mean doesn't need to increase that much to completely wreck your network. Another surprising fact I might add, is by toning down std, we can still keep values under control, but up until a point only. $(1.5, 0.0001)$ will still blow up as usual.

Lastly, negative mean seems to act the same as positive mean. This is understandable, as only signs were flipped, not the tensor scale themselves:

In [32]:
analyze(-0.5, 1)
Out[32]:
([-0.4896994, 0.0282136, -0.0082183, 0.0027812, -6.16e-05, -0.0010862],
 [0.9956397, 2.7155051, 5.6108146, 2.251837, 0.0561705, 0.0978187])
